1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:15,160
 Catholic education is about the salvation of the souls of the students and also the souls of the teachers and administrators. It's about the salvation of souls. It's the mission of the church to populate the kingdom of heaven with people who are saved in Jesus Christ.

2
00:00:15,160 --> 00:00:28,840
 Everything else is downstream from that, whether it's learning math or learning science or getting into a good college or getting a good job, all of that is far downstream from the goal in view, which is the salvation of souls.

3
00:00:28,840 --> 00:00:54,840
 Okay. To the degree that artificial intelligence can serve as a positive tool for that end of real, authentic Christian human formation, great. Where it impedes that or becomes part of the mechanistic, do a Prussian model of just producing factory bots, we should throw it out.

4
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:07,840
 Well, Father Ambrose, thank you so much for joining us in the Gregorian studio and being here for the Builders AI Forum.

5
00:01:07,840 --> 00:01:13,840
 It's my pleasure. Thank you for the invitation, Ben. I'm happy to be here. Always happy to be in Rome and happy to be speaking with you today.

6
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:33,480
 Yeah, no, we're very, very blessed. And on this first day here at the forum, Father, I wanted to speak with you a little bit about AI and education in particular, and to look at how AI is accelerating certain opportunities in the education space, and also kind of the problems that you see in your work, in particular with the Evermode Institute.

7
00:01:33,840 --> 00:01:40,300
 My confers and I have developed an online curriculum to teach the faith to Catholic school teachers and administrators.

8
00:01:40,840 --> 00:01:52,780
 The Catholic school system is kind of a disaster in America. It needs renewal. And one piece that needs renewal is the catechetical formation of the faculty and administration.

9
00:01:52,780 --> 00:02:00,540
 Okay, so that's what we're working on. We use AI for that in this way. We've developed an online platform.

10
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:14,420
 My developers, in fact, the developer was a cameraman who taught himself how to code by using AI technology online right now to build out a platform.

11
00:02:14,420 --> 00:02:15,040
 Wow.

12
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:20,720
 So that's a very practical, immediate, technical use of AI that's been extremely successful in my experience.

13
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:24,420
 Now, that's not in the classroom. That's behind what's going on in the classroom.

14
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:43,600
 My team of lay people who help us Norbertines to film, well, create film, and then deploy our catechetical curriculum, use AI to help generate texts, scripts.

15
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:51,040
 I never use those just off the shelf, as it were, from AI. It always needs a human touch.

16
00:02:51,400 --> 00:03:04,740
 But the team of people who help me to do what I do best as a priest, kind of with the public face of this program, they can line up for me the working materials from which I can then do my priestly work.

17
00:03:04,740 --> 00:03:18,740
 It's like a research tool almost, or it's a library. I almost said biblioteca because we're in Italy, but it's a library of a sort that then I can reference and then do my work.

18
00:03:18,740 --> 00:03:21,960
 Okay, so that's been extremely helpful so far as a tool.

19
00:03:21,960 --> 00:03:36,700
 I see future possibilities in this. For example, we've rolled out the curriculum in an archdiocese that is mostly English-speaking, but with a heavy Spanish-speaking component.

20
00:03:37,220 --> 00:03:49,040
 And so the teachers are asking me, is this curriculum in Spanish? And I tell them, well, no, but within the next 12 months, I would like to put the whole curriculum in Spanish, and AI will help me to do that, me and my team.

21
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:51,740
 We'll be able to take all of the filmed contents.

22
00:03:52,640 --> 00:04:07,360
 As it is right now, we can generate transcripts in all the languages, but I'm interested to see how AI technology can help us to refine, hone, sharpen the instruments that we already have created, if that makes sense.

23
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:17,200
 What do you think, when you look at the broader landscape in Catholic education, needs to change so that there is that proper formation where people know what life is really truly about?

24
00:04:17,200 --> 00:04:28,080
 Okay, so that's a great question. And actually, it's the intersection of where this technology meets one of the big problems, which is a more theoretical problem with education as such.

25
00:04:28,860 --> 00:04:44,760
 Much of American education, I'd say all of Western education, but it's obvious my experience is in America, is in the United States, and in Catholic schools also, we have adopted the Dewey model, the Dewey model of a very utilitarian approach to education.

26
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:51,680
 So you get a good grade, you get into a good college, you get a good job so that you can make a lot of money and rinse, wash, and repeat through the generations.

27
00:04:51,680 --> 00:04:54,700
 This is not human. This is capitalism.

28
00:04:54,700 --> 00:05:04,940
 This is the industrial revolution of the 19th century and before, philosophically before, applied to education so that it's a factory line production.

29
00:05:04,940 --> 00:05:12,500
 It reaches back to Prussia. It was a military thing, you know, even the fact that students sit in rows, in seats.

30
00:05:12,500 --> 00:05:15,300
 I don't have been too excited and having trouble just focusing.

31
00:05:15,300 --> 00:05:24,680
 All of this, and the bell rings, all of this is modeled on military formation so that we can deploy an army of utilitarian bosses.

32
00:05:24,700 --> 00:05:32,620
 In a capitalistic culture for production, that's where it comes from. It's not human.

33
00:05:32,620 --> 00:05:48,020
 So rethinking or remembering what the formation of the person is, what Catholic education is, what education is, you know, we can look all the way back to the pre-Christian times of the Greeks and the Romans about virtue.

34
00:05:48,020 --> 00:05:51,500
 What is virtue? What is virtue? What does it mean to be a human being as such?

35
00:05:51,500 --> 00:05:56,860
 And then how do we form someone into the life where they can be happy, a life of virtue?

36
00:05:56,860 --> 00:06:00,680
 And ultimately, of course, as Christians, we know that means a life of grace, sanctifying grace.

37
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:02,900
 We need to help.

38
00:06:02,900 --> 00:06:05,500
 So this is all very, I know it's a very high level.

39
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:09,500
 This is kind of 30,000 foot theoretical conversation so far, but I'm going to make it practical.

40
00:06:09,620 --> 00:06:10,740
 I'll try to make it practical.

41
00:06:10,740 --> 00:06:18,660
 Education, Catholic education is about the salvation of the souls of the students and also the souls of the teachers and administrators.

42
00:06:18,660 --> 00:06:20,020
 It's about the salvation of souls.

43
00:06:20,020 --> 00:06:28,260
 It's the mission of the church to populate the kingdom of heaven with people who are saved in Jesus Christ.

44
00:06:29,860 --> 00:06:36,060
 Everything else is downstream from that, whether it's learning math or learning science or getting into a good college or getting a good job.

45
00:06:36,060 --> 00:06:42,060
 All of that is far downstream from the goal in view, which is the salvation of souls.

46
00:06:42,060 --> 00:06:54,760
 To the degree that artificial intelligence can serve as a positive tool for that end of real, authentic Christian human formation, great.

47
00:06:54,760 --> 00:07:08,040
 Where it impedes that or becomes part of the mechanistic, do a Prussian model of just producing factory bots, we should throw it out.

48
00:07:08,040 --> 00:07:15,440
 So I think that this is the role of teachers in the classroom to say, listen, it might be, and I'm kind of a purist about this.

49
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:16,640
 I went to a liberal arts college.

50
00:07:16,640 --> 00:07:18,300
 I was trained by the Jesuits.

51
00:07:18,300 --> 00:07:19,840
 I went to a Jesuit boys' school.

52
00:07:19,840 --> 00:07:22,320
 And I'm a middle-aged man.

53
00:07:22,320 --> 00:07:24,640
 I grew up without any of this stuff.

54
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:30,180
 And I think it's really devastating for young people to be on a screen all the time.

55
00:07:30,440 --> 00:07:43,900
 I think that in an ideal Catholic family, a child would not even have a screen in front of him or her ever, seriously, ever, until maybe they're 12 or 15.

56
00:07:43,900 --> 00:07:47,940
 They would never have access to the internet or a cell phone until they're 18.

57
00:07:47,940 --> 00:07:50,560
 Now, is that going to happen in North America?

58
00:07:50,560 --> 00:07:51,400
 Probably not.

59
00:07:51,880 --> 00:08:16,080
 So, but how can we avoid the dangers of artificial intelligence and other technologies that give us the illusion of somehow knowing when, in fact, we've just outboarded all of that exploration and cognition and mental exploration to a machine?

60
00:08:17,280 --> 00:08:20,140
 So, that's a theoretical challenge.

61
00:08:20,140 --> 00:08:26,700
 And I think that the answer to that comes down, Ben, to what is artificial intelligence?

62
00:08:26,700 --> 00:08:30,480
 It's not ever going to be intelligence.

63
00:08:30,480 --> 00:08:36,940
 It will always be artificial because intelligence is something that requires a rational soul.

64
00:08:36,940 --> 00:08:41,200
 Only humans and angels and demons have such a soul.

65
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:45,480
 So, all of it is just simply an artifact.

66
00:08:46,840 --> 00:08:51,000
 It's a technological artifact and it can't replace human intelligence.

67
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:52,180
 Does that make sense?

68
00:08:52,180 --> 00:09:07,600
 But, Father, what do you say to that when almost on some level, like the underlying principles of this technology are embedded in a transhumanist ideology, which is, of course, the opposite on so many levels to the faith or the truths of the faith?

69
00:09:08,720 --> 00:09:24,180
 I think that, well, it means that we have to be very circumspect and prudent about how we use it, how we deploy it, knowing that this technology is not necessarily in its creation at the service of a common good.

70
00:09:25,560 --> 00:09:29,220
 And is it at the service of an evil end?

71
00:09:29,220 --> 00:09:30,340
 I'm not convinced of that.

72
00:09:30,340 --> 00:09:32,880
 I don't know that it's – I think it's morally neutral.

73
00:09:34,020 --> 00:09:45,140
 I was having a conversation earlier today with somebody who was in Silicon Valley, very, very well placed in all of the big companies that you would know from Intel to Microsoft to Amazon.

74
00:09:45,600 --> 00:09:51,800
 And he was describing how the engineering departments were creating all of the algorithms that we all live with.

75
00:09:52,760 --> 00:10:09,440
 I'll just use one as an example that, you know, the algorithms on, let's say, something like Amazon or Amazon Prime are designed specifically to capitalize upon those people in the ecosystem who are going to become addicted to the use of this platform.

76
00:10:09,440 --> 00:10:11,180
 So what does that settle into?

77
00:10:11,180 --> 00:10:20,280
 It settles into the people who have the least amount of money but the greatest propensity to spend on loan, to rack up debt.

78
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:25,700
 And that's the demographic that is most lucrative, which is, of course, not human at all.

79
00:10:25,700 --> 00:10:26,540
 In fact, it's abusive.

80
00:10:26,540 --> 00:10:27,620
 It's terrible, yeah.

81
00:10:27,620 --> 00:10:41,760
 But the technology itself is not concerned about that because what was the motivation creating it to capitalize to algorithms, AI-generated algorithms, that make it the bottom line, the supreme end?

82
00:10:41,760 --> 00:10:48,960
 And it doesn't matter who they're stomping all over or whose lives they're ruining to get to that end.

83
00:10:48,960 --> 00:10:58,040
 Okay, so that means that we Catholics and people who are thinking about these and willing to use these technologies, we can supply the proper end in view.

84
00:10:58,520 --> 00:11:21,580
 We can say, okay, listen, the bottom line is not the be-all, end-all, but the common good of a culture or the individual good of the soul concerned, the person concerned, is more important than the instrumentalization of that person for a capitalistic end or some other end that would be just using the person as an instrument.

85
00:11:23,140 --> 00:11:24,320
 We can provide that.

86
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:34,280
 Now, can we change the—can we inform the, as you said, the transhuman motivation that is the very origin of that?

87
00:11:34,700 --> 00:11:49,460
 Maybe, if we convince the people, the so-called Silicon Valley giants who are really the drivers of this movement, if we can convince them that there's a higher good than the bottom line.

88
00:11:49,460 --> 00:11:55,420
 Now, I mean, that's really what the church has always been—we're supposed to be a light in the world, right?

89
00:11:55,440 --> 00:11:59,640
 The church is the light, that Christ is the light of the world, and we reflect that light.

90
00:11:59,640 --> 00:12:01,980
 Not everyone's going to see it.

91
00:12:01,980 --> 00:12:15,780
 And that means that we, like I said, we have to be circumspect and prudent about how we use a technology that is going to be inclined toward the instrumentalization of the human person.

92
00:12:15,780 --> 00:12:17,640
 What does that mean?

93
00:12:17,940 --> 00:12:23,220
 Like I said, I think for a family, it means probably don't give your child an iPhone until they're 18.

94
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:29,960
 That seems to mean, as a priest, to be a very prudent thing.

95
00:12:29,960 --> 00:12:36,620
 Now, then, of course, I don't have a family of my own, so I don't know what that's like to have the 12-year-old come home and say, but all of my friends have one.

96
00:12:37,340 --> 00:12:39,880
 Then you, of course, have the movement of families to say, well, you know what?

97
00:12:39,880 --> 00:12:47,400
 We probably shouldn't have our kids in the public school then, and probably not in the Catholic school then either, unless the Catholic school is the kind that is on board with that approach.

98
00:12:47,400 --> 00:12:54,340
 So then we think, okay, well, are we going to circle the wagon so much that our children then don't engage with the culture at all?

99
00:12:54,340 --> 00:12:55,880
 Well, no, that's not probably a good idea either.

100
00:12:57,700 --> 00:13:12,000
 I'm highlighting for you, Ben, and for our viewers and listeners just how deeply we need to think about the ramifications of the individual choices we make in the application, in the use of these technologies.

101
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:16,780
 These are important decisions at every moment.

102
00:13:16,780 --> 00:13:22,460
 And I guess, Father, where would you draw the line in the classroom as well?

103
00:13:22,980 --> 00:13:35,300
 I'm strongly against the replacement of person-to-person education in the classroom for education of elementary school or high school or probably even university.

104
00:13:35,300 --> 00:13:42,300
 I think that that's a bad idea to try to replace real professors and teachers.

105
00:13:42,300 --> 00:13:44,620
 And, you know, education is a leading.

106
00:13:44,620 --> 00:13:46,320
 It's to lead out.

107
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:52,460
 Educate is to lead out, out of darkness into the light, out of ignorance into knowledge.

108
00:13:52,900 --> 00:14:02,720
 That requires a human being who leads somebody, who is the teacher, almost like taking somebody by the hand and bringing them, come along with me.

109
00:14:02,720 --> 00:14:05,220
 I want to show you what I know, what I've discovered.

110
00:14:05,220 --> 00:14:06,860
 Let's go look for the truth together.

111
00:14:06,860 --> 00:14:08,500
 A machine can never be that.

112
00:14:08,500 --> 00:14:10,680
 Where could we use it?

113
00:14:10,680 --> 00:14:19,080
 Well, like I described in the work that I'm doing, I think that we can use it as a tool to help those people, those real human people, do their work.

114
00:14:19,820 --> 00:14:24,440
 So this program that my convoyers and I have put together is, as I said, is virtual.

115
00:14:24,440 --> 00:14:34,600
 The teachers either watch videos together as a faculty and then discuss them, or they go home, depending on their school, and they watch the videos and then they have their assessment questions.

116
00:14:34,600 --> 00:14:49,980
 Okay, so I'm interested to see over the next 9 to 12 months how we can use AI technology as a personal teaching agent, personal learning, so that that teacher watches the video and AI helps them, helps us to assess, have they learned what they need to learn from that video?

117
00:14:49,980 --> 00:14:52,000
 You know, what was important to you?

118
00:14:52,020 --> 00:14:54,900
 And then the AI can, they type something in or speak something back.

119
00:14:54,900 --> 00:14:58,300
 Then the AI says, okay, well, did you think about this?

120
00:14:58,300 --> 00:15:02,820
 So, and that's, I think that we are at a point where the technology can do that.

121
00:15:03,360 --> 00:15:18,160
 And that way, without my being able to teach personally 2,500 educators across the country to be sure that they watched, that they heard what I said, or my confere said, and understood it, we can use AI technology to do that.

122
00:15:18,160 --> 00:15:18,800
 These are adults.

123
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:20,260
 These are busy people.

124
00:15:20,620 --> 00:15:22,260
 And they're the ones who are teaching the children.

125
00:15:22,260 --> 00:15:29,060
 Now, what I, I would not want to replicate that in the classroom for the 12-year-old or the 18-year-old or even for the 20-year-old.

126
00:15:29,060 --> 00:15:34,740
 But I think it's a tool that can help at the back end to prepare the teacher.

127
00:15:34,740 --> 00:15:38,420
 It's very similar to, you know, I preach a lot.

128
00:15:38,420 --> 00:15:41,880
 We priests have a lot of work to do, but we have, we have to be able to access.

129
00:15:41,880 --> 00:15:46,600
 Let's say, I want to know what St. John Chrysostom says about this passage of the scriptures.

130
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:47,700
 I can use a computer for that.

131
00:15:47,700 --> 00:15:52,240
 I can go back to my, my library shelf where I have St. Thomas Aquinas' Catena Aurea.

132
00:15:52,240 --> 00:15:58,440
 It was a technology from the 13th century where he took the fathers, digested them according to the gospels.

133
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:00,820
 So I can look at this chapter and verse.

134
00:16:00,820 --> 00:16:03,120
 St. Thomas Aquinas did this for me.

135
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:06,740
 It's an AI technology from the 13th century, right?

136
00:16:06,740 --> 00:16:07,780
 It's a tool.

137
00:16:07,780 --> 00:16:09,960
 And I can pull that off my shelf.

138
00:16:09,960 --> 00:16:13,160
 I can look, okay, here's what St. John Chrysostom says in St. Augustine.

139
00:16:13,160 --> 00:16:18,280
 And, you know, a kind of, it's a, but it's material.

140
00:16:18,280 --> 00:16:18,740
 Fantastic, yeah, yeah.

141
00:16:18,740 --> 00:16:21,940
 And, and it's of great use to me in my preaching.

142
00:16:21,940 --> 00:16:24,200
 And I can prepare my homily from that.

143
00:16:24,200 --> 00:16:25,320
 And I put the book back on the shelf.

144
00:16:25,320 --> 00:16:26,500
 And then I preach.

145
00:16:26,500 --> 00:16:28,400
 I write the homily.

146
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:29,120
 I prepare the homily.

147
00:16:29,120 --> 00:16:29,920
 But I preach.

148
00:16:29,920 --> 00:16:33,260
 And that in the background is a technology that's helped me.

149
00:16:33,260 --> 00:16:42,300
 I think similarly, like I just described, the AI engagement with the contents of the Evermode Institute curriculum can be that for the teacher.

150
00:16:42,300 --> 00:16:43,760
 They're learning the faith.

151
00:16:43,760 --> 00:16:49,120
 And then now he or she tells the students, who is Jesus Christ?

152
00:16:49,120 --> 00:16:50,640
 What is the sacrament?

153
00:16:50,640 --> 00:16:58,620
 How does the life of grace inform my work as a biology teacher for the, for the freshman in high school?

154
00:16:59,620 --> 00:17:01,140
 The AI is not doing that.

155
00:17:01,140 --> 00:17:02,240
 The teacher is doing that.

156
00:17:02,240 --> 00:17:12,980
 And our program, assisted by AI, at some very minimal level right now, but it could be more, is helping the teacher to be prepared well to do the teaching.

157
00:17:12,980 --> 00:17:13,700
 Does that make sense?

158
00:17:13,700 --> 00:17:16,100
 It's an instrument.

159
00:17:16,100 --> 00:17:16,600
 It's a tool.

160
00:17:16,600 --> 00:17:17,480
 It's a sharp tool.

161
00:17:17,480 --> 00:17:20,200
 It can never replace the human.

162
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:21,840
 I love that.

163
00:17:21,840 --> 00:17:23,700
 And, Father, one final question.

164
00:17:23,700 --> 00:17:29,420
 What are you most excited about to get out of this edition of the Builders AI form here in Rome?

165
00:17:29,420 --> 00:17:35,140
 And kind of a follow-up to that is, what is giving you hope when you look at the Catholic educational landscape in general?

166
00:17:35,140 --> 00:17:35,540
 Okay.

167
00:17:35,540 --> 00:17:36,860
 Two good questions.

168
00:17:36,860 --> 00:17:43,420
 A conference like this is always an opportunity to network with some of the people who are doing the most good

169
00:17:43,780 --> 00:17:54,160
 and who are the sharpest instruments, the sharpest tools in the toolbox in God's kingdom right now, thinking very creatively, working very hard.

170
00:17:54,160 --> 00:17:56,100
 These are the movers and the shakers.

171
00:17:56,100 --> 00:18:01,460
 And that's really fun to be in a group of people like that and to have conversations like this that we're having right now

172
00:18:01,460 --> 00:18:07,020
 or hearing from people in the conference contents, but especially in the networking that happens around it

173
00:18:07,020 --> 00:18:09,920
 to see where our worlds intersect and where we can support each other.

174
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:10,900
 I'm excited about that.

175
00:18:10,900 --> 00:18:13,900
 I always look forward to that in this kind of a conference.

176
00:18:13,900 --> 00:18:16,080
 It's my first time at the Builders AI forum.

177
00:18:16,080 --> 00:18:17,520
 So far, it's been a great day.

178
00:18:17,520 --> 00:18:23,320
 I'm a most – and the other one was, what am I excited about in Catholic education?

179
00:18:23,320 --> 00:18:24,260
 What gives you hope?

180
00:18:24,260 --> 00:18:28,580
 What gives me hope – this is going to sound strange given that this is a conversation about AI.

181
00:18:29,080 --> 00:18:39,540
 What gives me hope are those places like the Chesterton Academies, the classical Catholic startup schools,

182
00:18:39,540 --> 00:18:45,280
 very often outside of the – kind of on the periphery of ordinary Catholic education,

183
00:18:45,280 --> 00:18:55,460
 where families, parents, teachers, and also sometimes clergy, but that's usually not where the motivation comes from,

184
00:18:55,460 --> 00:18:58,880
 are throwing themselves into the best of the old.

185
00:18:58,880 --> 00:19:05,500
 Why can we put a school together where there is no screen, where there's no screen time?

186
00:19:05,500 --> 00:19:07,340
 That gives me hope.

187
00:19:07,340 --> 00:19:09,220
 Is that weird for AI?

188
00:19:09,220 --> 00:19:09,740
 I understand.

189
00:19:09,740 --> 00:19:15,160
 That gives me hope because I know that those people will be the ones who will understand how best to

190
00:19:15,160 --> 00:19:18,060
 confront the challenges when they come up against them.

191
00:19:18,060 --> 00:19:18,720
 Beautiful.

192
00:19:18,720 --> 00:19:20,800
 Well, Father Ambrose, thank you so much for your time.

